 HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomoftenacity>AtomOfTenacity </A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/27/02 10:57:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/atom_of_tenacity.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Star Wars – Giving Space Fans a Bad Rap?</span><hr size=1> Star Wars – probably one of the most well-known sci-fi films of the 20th Century. But is it really sci-fi? Although this question may seem ludicrous at first, an objective and closer examination reveals that Star Wars is in fact a movie based on space fantasy – not science fiction. <br>
So, why can this fact be damaging to space buffs and proponents of progress in general? The simple answer lies in that Star Wars and other films of its ilk are often associated with persons who promote space exploration et al, which isn’t necessarily always the case.<br>
When one is trying to have a meaningful conversation with another individual concerning the various aspects of space and science, it is not rare for the pro-spacer’s position to be brushed off with a remark such as “…oh…well, all that Stars Wars stuff is a bunch of bull” or something to that effect.<br>
This “guilt by association” has raised its ugly head on more then one occasion during many of my vocal conversations that I have had over the last few years. Instead of the person you are talking to thinking of the great sci-fi books and movies from the past that have actually inspired endeavors towards the conquest of space, one is confronted with the artificial nonsense of Star Wars.<br>
Star Wars was made for the masses to be consumed by the masses and thus it is not a valid representation of “hard science” in the least. <br>
In my humble opinion, Star Wars can easily be classified as yet another one of those bastions of pop culture that has not contributed to the cause of space – let its logos and images stay on Taco Bell cups and burrito wrappers – not the hallowed grounds of space history books or lingo.<br>
In closing, I’d like to admonish my fellow warriors for space to be wary of what is held up as sci-fi when often times it is actually science or space fantasy.<br>
Let’s not allow our status and esteem to be debunked by the pop culture backwardness of our day.   <br>
<br>
I know that this thread may invoke strong responses from its readers and so in advance I welcome your replies.<br>
<br>
AoT    <br>
