 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 287<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/28/02 12:07:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/pubimage.asp?id_=638250 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Star Wars – Giving Space Fans a Bad Rap?</span><hr size=1> I have to admit myself that I'm starting to develop a preference for &quot;realistic&quot; sci-fi over space fantasy like Star Trek and Star Wars.  I wish someone would make a compelling movie that would hint at the possibilities of space for human and economic expansion using technology that isn't necessarily out of our grasp, technology like space elevators and nuclear propulsion.  Even though there are plenty of movies that could fit this category none of them have reached the popularity of movies like Star Trek or Star Wars.  Don't get the idea I'm advocating making overly educational boring junk either.  I think we could come up with plenty of exciting plots within those constraints.  Project Orion's idea for a &quot;space adventure&quot; forum kind of fits into this category of sci-fi that's ardently conceivable but just out of reach at the moment.   <br>
<br>
Just imagine if Hollywood decided to make a movie showcasing Orion spacecraft.  They'd probably portray the crew of the spacecraft as baby killers and butchers of the environment in space that have to be stopped by some politically correct, irrationally anti-nuclear hero that would make constant wise cracks about those demons who believe in the use of nuclear power.  And the finale would come when the hero's little LOX rocket catches up to the Orion and the hero blows away the evil crew of the Orion.  It wouldn't surprise me.      <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 126<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/28/02 10:20:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Star Wars – Giving Space Fans a Bad Rap?</span><hr size=1> didn't &quot;Deep Impact&quot; feature an Orion?  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1298<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/28/02 10:32:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Star Wars – Giving Space Fans a Bad Rap?</span><hr size=1> I haven't seen Deep Impact, but a quick searched turned up the following:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Why was the Orion propulsion system chosen for the spacecraft?<br>
<br>
Orion was an idea for using a series of small nuclear explosions to propel spacecraft through the solar system. In the late 1950s and early 1960s, some of the best scientific minds on Earth worked on this project. Although a prototype using conventional explosives did fly, the nuclear-powered Orion was never developed. The prototype now hangs in the Smithsonian's National Air and Space Museum.<br>
<br>
The script required a spacecraft to carry a human crew quickly to the comet, but, as Griffin explained, &quot;We have no propulsion system capable of getting them to a comet. The old Orion system was Gene Shoemaker's idea. So we assumed it had been developed, and we scaled it up.&quot;<br>
<br>
Would Orion be a good choice for the mission? Ted Taylor of Princeton University, who headed the Orion project, said there are now &quot;much better choices than Orion,&quot; such as solar electric propulsion, which is soon to be demonstrated on the Deep Space 1 mission.<br>
<br>
The portrayal of Orion was one of Burke's greatest concerns -- he worked on the original Orion project. From reading the script, we couldn't tell how it would work or what it would look like, for that will be determined by special effects, which were not completed when this article was prepared. In places, the script seemed to indicate that Orion used a series of pulsed explosions to put-put-put through space -- which would be correct. In other places, it seemed to take off with one big bang, the acceleration from which, Burke pointed out, &quot;would instantly turn the astronauts to Jell-O.&quot;<br>
<br>
But if the effects are done correctly, what might an Orion-powered spacecraft look like to observers on Earth? Taylor described the possibilities: &quot;Most of what you'd see would be images, not of the explosions themselves, but of their effects on the upper atmosphere -- flashes of multicolored light.&quot; It might be possible to see &quot;the expanding explosion of each pulse, something like a bright cone. It might even be blinding.&quot;<br>
<br>
Taylor added an interesting sidelight: &quot;There was a time when Arthur C. Clarke planned to use Orion in 2001: A Space Odyssey. But they decided the special effects would be too complicated.&quot; We'll see how the makers of Deep Impact do.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
