y</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Star Wars – Giving Space Fans a Bad Rap?</span><hr size=1> Star Trek was origonaly a social commentary on America in the 1960-70's set in space like MASH was a comentary on Veitnam st in Korea. The idea of a world where all mankind is judged by their own abilities, not their race or sex, was hardly universal back then. Even TNG continued the tradition of a social commentary to some degree. Having african americans, asians, women, and even a russian cast in roles of authority was almost unprecidented in a TV show. Sure the science is unrealistic at many times, it was never the focus, only a means. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1308<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/29/02 10:28:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Star Wars - Giving Space Fans a Bad Rap?</span><hr size=1> I can't back this up with a reference, but I remember reading an article<br>
that stated the U.S. Navy toured the bridge set during the original <br>
Star Trek's network run.  They were so impressed with the <br>
circular layout, and the angled controls that they wanted to incorporate<br>
some of the design elements into Naval combat ships.<br>
